bio: Acquisitions Editor: @wpublishing | @harpercollins. Bestselling author. I love stories, writers & naps.

social_posts.post_text:
The post that was 3 years in the making. This was the moment right after I happy-bawled and they group hugged me because I did it. I finished the book I started writing 3 years ago. 😭😭😭😭😭😭 I feel speechless. Impossible. Three years. The hardest writing of my life. It is finished. And my people have cheered me and believed and encouraged me every single mile of this marathon. I made them agree to let me post this of us all in our Sunday afternoon sweats and crazy hair and exhausted joy because I needed to memorialize the moment to make it real so my brain can actually believe it.

If you prayed or sent me a message or Starbucks gift cards or encouraged me in any way in the last several years, please consider yourself part of this group hug too!! Book writing is a team sport; through other people is how Jesus gets His encouragement to us. Thank you for being mine. 

We fly home to South Africa next week, Saturday. What a grace, to now get to travel home to the place where the story started. 

Thank you for bearing witness with me. I have felt you with me and it’s pushed back against the loneliness in holy ways. You probably won’t hear me talk much about the book now until it comes out in the spring of 2024. But today is an Ebenezer, to mark the moment when we crossed the finish line. 

So grateful,
Lisa-Jo

5 years! Between these 2 photos! 5 years since the whole fam was home in South Africa. We’re about to fix that! By Monday we will be sleeping under my father’s thatch roof in the shade of the jacaranda tree where I buried my heart 28 years ago when I first left home. Going back to reclaim it, to drink and eat and laugh and love our way back into that place where our family has beds and all our favorite foods waiting and where we still remember the words of the love song that the stars of the southern cross sing under an African sky.
When you have an 18 hour layover in Cairo and a close local friend who is an Egyptologist—you go big before you keep going home!

Home. 
“Still I am certain to see the goodness of the Lord in the land of the living.” Psalm 27:13
We are outnumbered by teenagers and it’s the literal best.

NOT a typical day-in-the-life. All 27 of us immediate family are under this one thatch roof weekend tucked into a game preserve just outside of Pretoria, South Africa. It feels like being in a waking dream. Almost too beautiful to share. And almost too beautiful not to. How does one freeze frame the extraordinary to savor again on ordinary Tuesdays when you’re back at work? How does one hold onto each day just a little bit longer than 24 hours? How does one hold onto the closeness when distance looms on the horizon again? How does one eat enough of today to tide one over till tomorrow? With big bites. And laughter. And shared memory. And gratitude. And tears remembering this past year. And awe. And the smell of your hair after hours spent talking around the fire together. Proof that today really happened.
4 days off grid. 27 of us. Many languages, races, abilities, parents, stories — all one family.

Elephant whisperers 🐘🤯❤️Conservation works hand-in-hand with education and tourism in South Africa and we got to spend a truly astonishing day with third generation elephant handlers, who have dedicated their lives to the protection, care and advocacy for these giant leviathan creatures today. We learned how they can remember your scent, and even your name, and how you treated them decades after they first met you. The joy their human family had in sharing them with us was next level. How to even put into words what it feels like to stand beside a beast who humbles you by its sheer size and strength and willingness to play with you? The stereotype is that the lion is the king of the jungle. But South Africans will tell you, it is the elephant. If you are ever in South Africa, we cannot recommend highly enough the care, qualifications, and personal delight of @adventures_with_elephants at Zebula. We are all still shook from the glory of today. And so grateful for the people dedicated to preserving this great species. Unreal. Just unreal.

Hi mom— remember how much you disliked how short your name was? “Just Jo” no middle name. No “e.” Remember how often your family moved, how you traveled from school to school, how you so badly wanted to leave a mark on the world, how you loved poetry and plays and coke and chocolate and cheese puffs and planned to write a book but never did? 

Check it — all 4 of us inherited your name! You gave it to me and I gave it to my firstborn and both your sons passed it to their daughters. Lisa-Jo, Jackson Jo, Mackenzie Jo and Anna Jo. We LOVE chocolate, and Coke and movies and books and stories and cheese puffs (especially after they’ve gone just that little bit stale and crunchy). And we LOVE your name. And here we are today — all 4 of your Jos — a little sunburned from a day of swimming, but stuffed full of chocolate cake and chips and a whole lot in love with this family — and this name — you left us. ￼❤️

I’m only here in your country for another 2 days but I’ve stocked piled moments like these with my son and my nieces- your grandkids who you would have ADORED and we keep remembering you and writing new pages in your book. 

It’s a really good book, mom.

First time in 5 years Christmas was in person and not on FaceTime. When I’m 90 I’ll still be able to lie in bed and retrace the outlines of this glorious day with all my people. I’ll never forget my kids making core memories under the hot sun of a South African Christmas. Much was dark and fraught this year. But these people have blazed like a comet of Christ with us, Immanuel, through the longest year. They are the only gift I wanted this year. The best gift. My heart is so full it is spilling out of my eyes. And I don’t want to miss even a second of a blink in this place.

My father is my native land. The longitude and latitude of all my childhood joy and sorrow. He smells like soft, worn in leather and his hands are the tools of his trade — sheep farmer turned bush doctor turned inner city family doctor. He once pulled a toothpick out of my foot. I once helped him stitch up his own hand. Those hands are now a map of veins as blue as the South African sky, pockmarked by age and the wrinkles of a southern cross galaxy of age spots and freckles and faith after years of folding them in prayer. 

I am his oldest child and eldest daughter and we have travelled backroads together through dark nights and we have arrived into the wide open fields of God’s grace and human do-overs and it’s taken more than half both our lives and it has been worth it. 

My father is my native land and I take his story with me when I leave. And I feel it like so much treasure in my carryon. Or is that my heart. 

This is my last night in my Father’s house and I’m not ready to say goodbye.

My son, Micah asked: how do you go back to your normal life after a trip like this?

My husband answered, you don’t.

You let yourself be changed. You see the world through wider eyes, where America isn’t the main character in the story. You let it all in, the joy and beauty of an inheritance in a family in another country. And the sadness and loss of living so far away. You learn what it feels like to be a bridge. You lay yourself down between continents and let your heart go back-and-forth.

And this is a good and a terrible thing. The intimate knowing of a place and people and language just out of reach but never not your home.

We shared a lot of beauty out of South Africa the last month. A feast, it’s true. But what made it so sweet. So tender. So unspeakably miraculous. Is that it was like a feast served in the presence of our enemies — cancer and chemo and surgery and transplants. The Lord spread a table of infinite kindness and goodness for our family; He laid us down in green pastures after months and months of the desert of barely daring to hope. 

Both my brothers battled cancer this last year. One of them in the midst of his 4th child being born. Anyone who loves someone who’s fought this fight knows it costs all of you. It leaves scars. It is brutal. The treatment almost as terrible as the disease. We lived face down to the ground this past year — and many loaned us their faith on the days the only prayers we had were -please, God. Please. 

No new year is guaranteed. Not even tomorrow. We live on DAILY bread. And we discovered these last 18 months it is enough. But it leaves you changed. In every way. So to be gathered together for Christmas and not for a funeral — it was the only gift we wanted. And I am so deeply aware of how thin the veil is between our story and those of so many of you who had a different ending. So I hold space for your grief. 

Our suffering this past year has been where we have collided with God’s most tangible presence. I have no other way to explain it other than we believe in Jesus — the Son of suffering. And his intimacy defies the lie that prosperity = blessing. And instead the terrible tender truth is that, “𝗕𝗹𝗲𝘀𝘀𝗲𝗱 are those who 𝙢𝙤𝙪𝙧𝙣 for 𝙩𝙝𝙚𝙮 shall be comforted.” Matthew 5:4 

We felt that comfort in both our darkest nights and our brightest days. And we don’t take tomorrow for granted. But we do trust Jesus to be there, whatever this year holds.

I have a secret. 🤫☺️But first, hey, hi, I am Lisa-Jo. I was going to make one of those “start here” reels with video clips and photos telling you a bit about who I am and my decade online but honestly, the thought of it just made me tired. So, instead I’m going to write to you. Which makes more sense, since I am a writer and an editor. 

I started as a blogger over a decade ago. And I wrote three books. The first one from the tiny corner desk, in a tiny bedroom in a rental house surrounded by my kids’ legos and toys that would randomly start beeping or singing when I was trying to write at 4am before I had to head to my full time job by 8. I wrote my second and third books from my dining room table and finished my fourth one that will come out next year from the first home office space I’ve ever owned. It still takes my breath away to be greeted by these blue bookshelves every morning where I have my own desk in a room of my own. ￼

Since I started writing online I’ve gone from three toddlers who are now teens to three books and two Bible studies, a whole bunch of speaking opportunities I’ve treasured, and one podcast and my love for writing has spilled over into a passion for bringing the stories of other writers into the world. So, now I work full time from my home office and blue bookshelves as an acquisitions editor for @wpublishing — part of the @harpercollinschristian family and my secret is this: that it feels almost illicit to get to edit someone’s book. When it’s still naked. It doesn’t have covers yet or paper or ink. It is still digital. It exists in the ether, it’s an idea. It’s a naked, sacred idea.  Does that sound weird? What I mean is￼ to be invited into the incubation stage is both miraculous and astonishing. And I love it with my whole heart. ￼

The photo that hangs over my shoulder is my mom. She was always going to write a book, but passed away before she could. I love that I get to do this now for her and for me. Oh and I am originally from South Africa so you’ll hear my accent come and go. My reels are full of our most recent trip home. Thanks for being here. Now—tell me about a book that changed you. ￼❤️

My husband’s been out of town for a week or so. And today (when I was doing yet *another* sports pick up that he usually drives) I was winding too fast around the curves of Forest Avenue because I was listening to one of my favorite South African artists. The late afternoon sun cut through the naked trees and blinded me along with this thought — this is Pete’s music. As long as I’ve known him my music has been deeply influenced by his passion for finding new sounds and albums. I’m more often than not listening to the music that Peter loves. We have shared the same soundtrack for nearly 3 decades now, since he was a 21-year-old Michigander, who was already listening to South African music back before world music got trendy, and before he ever met me. And here I am, nearly 3 decades later, and his music is still filling my car and that place right under your ribcage. 

Today, I got gas, did the afternoon school run, said yes to Taco Bell and the lacrosse pick up match tomorrow (all the things he usually handles when he’s home) and realized that, until it’s missing, you can stop noticing your favorite music always playing in the background. Until it’s turned off. And with him being away, I noticed that the music was missing. And it made me the good kind of homesick.

Accurate. #writinglife 
Original video via @vertikaljumpreunion

Some middle aged thoughts about love 🙃❤️👉🏻It’s weird how much I love the last minute Valentine’s shoppers. There’s something about the desperation of dads and teenage boys, tired moms and toddlers all combing through the leftover cards, their eyes glazed over, their hands filled with half deflated heart balloons and tired roses that makes me want to watch them longer than is actually polite. 

I think I like that weird, industrial-sized, consumer holiday so much because my mom was crazy for it. It’s the only one I remember her really going all out for. She was the mom who constantly burned the dinner because she was caught up in a good book and forgot to pick us up from school because she had snuck out to an afternoon movie. But Valentine’s—she went all out. So each year as I wander the aisles with the leftover candies I’m the one imagining the stories behind the people with their hearts on their sleeves as well as in their hands

It’s followed so quickly by ashes on our foreheads and the season of Lent. Another love story. A deeper one. The kind of love that is willing to die unrequited, but hopeful. 

On Feb 14 I bought a car full of dollar store helium balloons and a cookie cake the size of my head for my kids. On Feb 22 I stood in my oldest leggings and rattiest sweat shirt and received the ashes of Lent. On Feb 24 I stood at the gravesite of my father in law and spent a weekend soaking in the stories of a family gathered from all over the country to love each other beyond ashes and dust. 

It’s the love story that holds. God and grandparents. Cousins, red eye flights and prayer. Jets pizza and memories. You can resurrect life out of almost any grief with the faithful love of an ordinary family. The kind that believes Jesus really did go to prepare a place for the people He loved to death. With the promise that He’d be waiting on the other side—arms wide open. Maybe with the heavenly equivalent of Jets Pizza and a whole fleet of race cars to work on. ☺️

An ending. 10 years of public teaching and speaking all over the country and one never to be forgotten trip to Italy to serve military families. I will never not desperately love the local church. The big, the small, the old school, the awkward, the dated, and the trendy new iterations.—I am indelibly marked by the faithful, joyful, insanely creative ways in which local churches all over the country serve their communities. Pastors have opened their pulpits to me, women’s ministries have trusted me with their events, and I’ve heard the stories of thousands of women and I never never never get tired of hearing how Jesus has left trails through their lives. We’ve cried and hugged and sipped so many cups of tea until we felt like family.

Last night was my last commitment. I’ve known for a while now it would be. I’ve been anticipating this new season of a new kind of work. But man, I sat in my car in the parking lot afterwards as it started to snow and let the doxology just wash over me, awed by it all. I’m at the airport now wearing my oldest boots and comfiest jeans headed home and my heart is so full— Praise God from Whom All Blessings Flow. Amen and amen.

OK friends, I don’t know how your day is going, but this might make you feel better about yourself. I just went to pick up the Subway order I had placed online only to discover I had placed it at a different location that I’ve never heard of but apparently selected since I was trying to go too fast 😂🤦🏼‍♀️

On the outside I might be a grown human helping authors develop their new book ideas. But on the inside I’m basically that stray sock that gets lost in the dryer for weeks and emerges confused, disoriented and wondering where everyone else went. 😂

Make me feel better about myself. Tell me your most recent human fail? 🤪

Been waiting to share this since Christmas. Even when a year can take your breath away with all its fear and sadness —somehow God is still there. Still making all things new. Not the same. Not fixed. Not perfect. And not how we might have imagined. But new. Every time I watch this I remember how it felt in my body. The shock. The instant tears. The grabbing and hugging each other. Our kids all bearing witness (watching my sons watch my reaction is one of my favorite bits of a favorite moment). Strangely the terrible moments from the same year had a lot of the same hallmarks. A time to weep and a time to laugh. Both sacred ground that Jesus calls, home.

If redemption were a season it would be spring. And “by March I am so hungry for spring I can hardly stand it.” I feel the ground under my feet groaning for new life. These are the times I turn to the gardeners. The people who teach us that “we need waking up after a long winter.” The people who believe because they see that “resurrection is a way of daily living.” My oldest friend is my most tender gardener—her words water me with hope and all my winters she has born witness to and never once stopped believing that spring was coming. In our home, our marriage, our children, our work, our calling, our community. Her book is coming now when we need it most. “Hopelessness“ she writes, “is a dreary experience, it doesn’t ask much of us. But the practice of resurrection is active and hopeful, and built on faith. Perhaps it isn’t even possible to practice resurrection on our own. Perhaps it is a way of living. That works best when we are living from within relationship and community.“ 

It is the only way I know that our deepest hurts find healing. 

A Home in Bloom: Four Enchanted Seasons with Flowers by @christiepurifoy
Puppies for your Friday!— our sweet dog had her first litter and we were all reunited today. May your weekend be filled with the joy of a 12 year old girl with an arm full of puppies, friends. ☺️🐶

I have written in kitchens, school pick up lines and parking lots waiting on a thousand soccer or football or lacrosse practices to end. I’ve written in coffee shops between school drops offs, in borrowed offices over the weekends, in friend’s spare bedrooms, at my dining room table, in between nursing, diaper changes and new jobs. I have never found an “ideal stretch of writing time” — I have fought to force my brain to make the most of the time I have. Sometimes it’s long and uninterrupted. Sometimes it’s stolen in snatches. Sometimes it’s early in the morning, sometimes it’s horribly late at night, sometimes it’s for blissful full days. What matters is the next sentence, the new idea, the rabbit trail of connections made, the vital edit. What doesn’t matter is the perfect place or time. Neither exist. I have fought the constant frustration of not enough of either. I write anyway. You can too. 🖤💪🏻⌨️

She would lose her mind if you drank the last of the Coke or ate the last of the chocolate. She would send you down to the corner store late at night on your bike to replenish her stock when she was in the thick of a translation project. She spoke so many languages. 

I lost my mind last week when my teenager finished the Coke and my waffles. He said they were delicious. I wanted to yell at him and instead I laughed so hard I could hardly stand as he came over chuckling out an apology and wrapped his man-arms around me and whispered in my ear how he had 2 for breakfast and then the last 2 for an after school snack. His dad filmed it all on his phone and my heart stretched like so much hot taffy between the then and the now.

I heard a song today while I was editing parts of that long ago story I lived with her with a line that maybe I want tattooed on my arm, my gravestone, my soul: “Just me and all of my Plain Jane glory.” 

We share a story of two sons and a daughter and laughter and soft hips and joy and cravings and books and poetry and I walk beside deep, still waters of memory and lie down in the green pastures of her story, inviting my kids to follow. 

Me and all of my plain Jane Glory. 

Don’t believe the commercials that tell you life is just some series of boxes you have to check or you’ve failed: marriage, house, kids, 401K, corner office, retirement plans, influence, and good photo editing skills. 

None of that goes with you. 

Life is a series of fits and starts and empty waffle boxes and so many breaks in your heart some days you can’t actually fathom how it keeps beating in your chest. But that, that you get to take with you. The sticky, complicated mess of everyday love. That comes. Every drop of it. 

That becomes part of your story. It fuses with your soul. 

You and all of your plain Jane Glory.

I impulsively cut 4 inches off my hair. Life here lately has been slower, softer, with time for deeper breaths. I had completely forgotten what it’s like to not work every weekend. Maybe one day I’ll be able to eat at a Panera again without having “weekend office” PTSD vibes. I don’t have anything deep to tell you. Just that things don’t stay the same. Even the hardest things. There is hope ahead, brave heart. And it looks like the gift of your ordinary life.

Love is the long game. The thousand hours at soccer fields on holiday weekends. The thousand miles of school commutes. The thousand dishes loaded and thousand tshirts folded. The thousand different ways to say I’m sorry. The thousand do-overs. The thousand nights shared—bad dreams, sweet talks, slow kisses, silent hands held, blankets shared, snoring tolerated. The thousand prayers, pleas, fears, tears. A thousand ways to know and be known. The thousand stray socks picked up, cupboards closed, tanks of gas, bags of groceries, petty fights. The thousand times you got it wrong. The thousand ways you tried again. And some days didn’t. Until you both caught your breath and remembered the thousand ways you can make each other laugh.  You are the keepers of each other’s best and worst thousand memories. The thousand ordinary ways to keep saying I do. Love is the long game.

“How you define success matters,“ he told me for the thousandth time. He was weeding. And before he scrubbed his arms with dish soap after he pulled out what might have been poison oak, he said it again. You’ve got everything you could want. Boots kicked off at the door. Dirty dishes. A sink full of last night’s memories and a thousand stories of how we got here. Long conversations with kids on the threshold of adulthood. Friends willing to cry with you. Updates from family around the corner, the state, the sea. A great find on Facebook marketplace. Good music blowing in from the neighbor’s backyard. A book you’ve meant to read. A library card. A heart that remembers what it feels like to be broken. The man whose known you for decades and keeps all your dreams as close as his own. Tacos and ice cream sandwiches. Give me all your basic Saturdays. Please and thank you.

Father-ing is risky business. So is daughter-ing. 
No one makes it through without scars. ￼
We are all a patchwork quilt of our father’s passions and failures, the face of their expectations.
I don’t know a dad that doesn’t get it wrong.
I’ve been a daughter who put an ocean between me and my origin story.
But our ending got re-written.
Through hard conversations and forgiveness. 
Some broken things can’t be fixed. 
But they can be made new. 
*Not overnight, but over decades*
Father-ing is risky business.
So is daughter-ing.

(my son watching us in that last frame. 😭🩷I could write a whole book about what it means to show our kids how not to repeat the stories of our fathers.)

Lisa-Jo Baker
#fathersday2023

I am still learning to speak teen girl. It’s not my native tongue. I was a motherless daughter and sister to all brothers. I have never been fluent in girl talk. And once upon a time I thought the worst thing that could happen to me was to be asked to mother a girl. That was 12 years ago. 

Slowly I am growing into a girl mom. Maybe it’s more accurate to say I am growing into *her* girl mom. We mother the kids who have been given to us. There is no one size fits all. Sometimes I wish there was. I lean toward laziness. Parenting keeps pulling me out of my comfort zone. She wants to speak quality time with me. So we carve out a weekend together in a sweet house loaned by a kind friend at the end of a quiet street with a dock and all the water washing in from the Chesapeake along with the whisper of paying attention. I slow down. I listen more than I speak. We try to eat every meal near the water. She tries crab cakes for the first time. I say yes to the half pound of fudge. We take the water taxi and good friends take us out on their boat. 

And in every mile traveled away from our routine, every sunset or paddleboard attempt or ice cream cone or parking spot navigated on a crowded street or cup of iced coffee or bridge walked across or pastry split or outfit change or playlist shared or houses admired or water we dangle our feet in or watermelon sliced or sunscreen applied or late night laughter I hear the words under the words—the whisper of I love you disguised as saying yes to what lights her up. 

It’s both harder and easier than I imagine. This business of being grown by my daughter. 

#surprisedbymotherhood

The next time you doubt your calling, your business plan, your parenting, your book, your story, your contribution, your art, your gifts, your voice — remember that the author of The Lord of the Rings once described his own work, as “a monster: an immensely long, complex, rather bitter, and very terrifying romance, quite unfit for children (if fit for anybody).“ JRR Tolkien.

This is your social media summer hall pass. 👉🏻slide 5 especially🤯

You are released from sharing the best places to eat in your hometown or that place you passed through once upon a time.
It’s time to enjoy that book, that song, that coffee machine, those sandals without having to source them.

You do not have to reply to every comment
You’re not required to respond to every DM
It’s not your job to find the links to every question about an item of clothing you were wearing, a piece of furniture you were sitting on or a recipe you were making.

You are not a tiny box on the Internet.
You do not have to live enmeshed with social media’s demands or timeline.

You are free to be free—to engage as much or as little as is healthy for
your soul.

You are not the Internet’s counselor, parent, pastor, or poet.

You do not have to sacrifice extra hours every day servicing strangers or managing other people’s opinions of you.

Photos can be taken with a blink, stored only in the memory files of your mind, turned into family stories instead of content.

You can share that photo of the fresh tomatoes sliced on your whole grain toast or

the quick pic you took of your Dunkin Donuts coffee that you raised to the heavens like a hallelujah right before you pulled out of the parking lot.

Just because they bring you JOY.

You are more than what meets the eye.

And not everyone on the Internet will fully appreciate that.
That’s OK.
As long as YOU do.
What your chaotic house REALLY says about you 😉🐉💪🏻

So, about that hard thing you think you should be over by now, that brutal break up or shocking job loss, that battle with cancer, that foreclosure, that life altering surgery, that parent you cared for who passed, that friend who quit you or  kid who hurt you or themselves, that diagnosis, that downsizing ,that church loss —how long did that drag out for ? A week? A month? A year? 

So, maybe stop telling yourself you should be over it by now OK? And instead expect AT LEAST that much time again to come out the other side. Ok? OK.

Love, LJ

#discover #surprisedbymotherhood #mentalhealthmatters

The life changing/saving magic of telling your story. As taught by my anesthesia addled mother. 😂😉💪🏻🔥

#explorepageready #mentalhealthtips #writeyourstory

How do you write a book? By keeping your butt in the chair. 😉🪑💪🏻 It’s that simple. And that incredibly difficult. You have to actually show up and do the work. Butt in chair. 

So much of life is the same isn’t it? Are we willing to keep showing up for the hard things? For the people we love? Through the dark valleys we want out of? For the sunrises that are hard to fathom might be coming our way. We need friends on the days it’s hard to stay in the chair. Friends who will stay with us. Who will believe in us and create with us and cheer for us and weep with us. Friends who believe the best about us and our people. Friends who see what we have missed. Friends who see us through the lens of Jesus and love us with his never giving up, always chasing you down kind of friendship love.

Friendship like that is 1000 kinds of gifts all in one. Today is my best-friend-like-a-sister, @annvoskamp’s birthday. 10 years ago, she taught us all how to start counting gifts, the hard, the terrible, the beautiful, the magnificent, the ordinary. I think all of those words perfectly describe her. What a gift you have been to millions of us, Ann! We’re so grateful God made you, our favorite Canadian farm girl! 🇨🇦🐷❤️

Thank you for staying in the chair. Thank you for the words you bring to us out of your own testimony of how God is always making His way to us. Thank you for teaching us to give thanks, to see the miracle in the brokenness, the gift in the story. 

We love you more than bacon. Happy Birthday!! 

👉🏻👉🏻feel free to drop a note for Ann below or go send her a birthday message on her stories today!

One day in class I pass him a note that must travel across every desk and through irritated hands all the way from one end of the room to the other to reach him. When it arrives at his elbow, I watch him unfold the tiny paper with his big hands. All it says is, “I just wanted to see if I could get this all the way across the classroom.” He flicks his green eyes in my direction. I am addicted to getting his attention. 

He is the straight-A professor favorite. I challenge everything. He smells like Polo Sport cologne and always lingers at dinner so that I have someone to sit with when I inevitably arrive late, rushed, and high from the intensity of my day in a city I am falling in love with. He watches me eat and listens as I tell him the details of my work. I don’t realize he is the man I am falling in love with. 

24 years and half my life later. The story is much the same. 

I tell him all my stores first. He helps me interpret them. Our three teenagers sit at the table with us now. And our sons smell like Polo Sport. His green eyes still keep me company and his big hands hold our family. 

He hugs me a sleepy goodbye as I slip out of bed for an early morning flight today. Our oldest drives me.  He knows it’s our anniversary. The sky is a love song to sunrise. He asks me — how long did you know dad before you started dating. I smile. “So,” I say. “I met him in DC when we were students, as you know…. “

I wasn’t sure how I would feel about today. I’ve watched it coming on the calendar out of the corner of my eye for a while now. Some milestones are like that. They loom large. We can’t quite make out if they’re monsters or monuments. A few weeks ago I asked him if we could plan to do something on this day together. He turned 18 a week ago. 

A week to the day after I turned 18 my father walked into our house from the hospice with my mom’s little blue suitcase in his hand. She wasn’t with him. That is the core memory I have of turning 18. It was the finish line of my childhood in every conceivable way. 

I wondered if the weight of watching my son turn that same age would hurt. The  opposite is true. In the upside down Kingdom of a God radically committed to making all things new, the last of my lingering pain around the memory of that day has been unmade. And the sorrow is softer. Healthier. As I look at my son in his beautiful 18th year. As I am here and alive to see it in my 49th I’m bowled over by the sheer delight of him and us and how this line didn’t hurt to cross after all. 

This year September 2nd is not a grave or a monster. It is an Ebenezer to new life. And a happy birthday for Jackson Jo and Lisa-Jo and Jo.
We have one year left with him at home. This is me trying to be brave.

I love my job and I have a crack in my tooth. The same tooth that already had a root canal. The same tooth that’s also next to the tooth that was extracted back in May. This is the way of life. I love my job and I have a crack in my tooth and I had a coupon for free munchkins at Dunkin’ Donuts today. I got six by accident and I’m happy about it. 

It’s raining and the cappuccino is really hot and my kitchen sink is full of dishes and my head is full of words and phrases and ideas and authors. 

My oldest is in the process of growing the most beautiful pair of wings. It hurts me when I look at them. But the good kind of hurt. The kind you feel when you look at great art. Sometimes when he comes home in the car he now drives his siblings in he stops by my office and hugs me for no reason. This also is a work of art. Ask any mother

They used to tell me that the days are long, but the years are short. I never would’ve believed I would try to stretch those days longer still. Like the last sip of a perfect cup of coffee or a sunset that’s disappearing, but you chase the flickering, dying, drowning pink across the sky anyway. You jump in your old car with your camera and your chase that sky as hard as you can. 

And some days as you finish your coffee, sipping slowly over your cracked tooth you get a text message with a photograph from one of your children who caught a sunset by the tail. And you know. these are the days of miracle and wonder and they are just the right length.

I stopped my work when I saw the shaft of sunlight gently hold the trashcan. I opened my office door. Rolled my stiff, computer bent neck.  I went outside. I crouched down to capture the moment. And then I wondered why trash cans and sunlight rate so high in their ability to move me. 

Some days I think my children are tired of hearing me, throat clogged with emotion, love sick again for the autumn colors that line our road. But then they text me photos of skylines and I know they have inherited more than just the color of my eyes. I am passing on a way of seeing.

When you are nearing 50 it’s easy to start to fear you haven’t left enough of a mark. Or that the only mark you’ve left are the scars your children bear. It is a tightrope walk of arriving and feeling left behind at the same time. How do make meaning from your mistakes, your losses, your scars?

Maybe you find a way to see the beauty in a trashcan. Light warms all our worst places. I walk back inside and call my long distance father and wish him happy birthday for my long gone mother. The divinity in our humanity bleeds through all our failures. God actually is with us. Even on the days when life is the trash can. He is the light. It’s so beautiful you can’t help but want to capture it.

To the mom with “that” kid this holiday. 🩷

#surprisedbymotherhood

This time of year can be a weird multiverse of all the year’s past hurts or disappointments. I don’t have a fix for that. I just have one tool to offer when the time is right for you. Studies show that, “Finding *positive meaning* in past negative memories is associated with enhanced mental health.” 😮🤯 Turns out our ability to make meaning out of painful memories can LITERALLY change how we experience those memories. 

Meaning is a powerful interpreter for pain. It doesn’t fix the pain. It doesn’t make the pain worth it. But it does *alter how you experience the memory.*

I spent 4 years writing a book that comes out in the spring. And the truth is — before a single person reads it—the book has changed my life. Because it helped me translate some of my worst memories into a deeply meaningful story. 

It was like setting myself free. 

It’s a slow process. But I recommend trying some version of it. Write. Journal. Talk to a therapist, a friend, process in your notes app. Find the meaning in any part of your past, and so many things in your present become easier to bear. Not fixed. Different. New. Free.

I hope some of your memories can become easier to hold this season, friends. 

Study Source: Speer, M.E., Ibrahim, S., Schiller, D. et al. Finding positive meaning in memories of negative events adaptively updates memory. Nat Commun 12, 6601 (2021). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-021-26906-4

The end of year panic is real. All the things you wanted to do and didn’t? Or all the things that went sideways? If only life had a “tap to complete” button, eh? 

I’m a sucker for watching a room remodeled, a house restored, a yard weeded, a pantry organized — all at the touch of a social media scroll. Hours, days, weeks fast tracked in seconds. If only. 

My mom was always going to write a book. But then she died at 42. It looked like the end of the story. Until her daughter grew up to become a writer and an editor who helps other people write books too. A generation. It took a WHOLE GENERATION for her calling and gifting to be realized. But even death couldn’t stop it.

We’re quick to assume we are too late. That the story’s over. That our family tree is too broken to replant. That nothing can grow in the rubbish soil we grew up in.

But God. He bridges generations. His promises last 1000s of years. You’re not too late. The best stories are the ones with lots of winding threads. Hard to follow. Astounding when we see the reveal at the end.

The promise to Moses of freedom and a new land was realized in Joshua. The promises of children, greatness, family to Sarah, Joseph, Ruth played out across decades. 

The end of this year is a comma friends. Just a comma in God’s good story. Not a period.

A full circle moment today. It’s a story that might encourage you. This morning I was sworn in as a CASA (Court Appointed Special Advocate) in some states they’re called a Guardian Ad Litem (GAL)—in the Baltimore city juvenile court system. 20 years ago, I started my career working in the child abuse and domestic violence section of the DC attorney general’s office. Since then I’ve worked in human rights overseas, as a blogger stateside, and most recently as an author and acquisitions editor. All of which I’ve loved. 

Then, like you, our world got really small the last several years. Until it had shrunk down to just our family and immediate friends, and, honestly, my laptop computer, and work from home. Then a big storm hit our family and we spent 3years just trying to survive; cancer and sorrow and chemo and heartache and doubt. Death took my father-in-law and one of our oldest best friends. But my brothers recovered. And slowly Pete and I started to look up again, look around outside the bunker we had been hunkered down in. 

Friends were going back to school, getting seminary degrees, inviting me to join, to study. All good and inspiring things. And yet none felt like what I was being called to.

I hope if you take one thing from this, it’s that we weren’t ready for the longest time. If you’re not ready, if you are in survival mode, if you are hunkered down, please receive my prayer of blessing, and that you sense the deep intimacy of the Holy Spirit in those dark valleys. Covering you. 

For us, years passed like that. Then as the sunlight came across the rim of where we had been hiding for so long, we heard the gentle voice of the Father God softly inviting us to step outside the nest again, and engage His world. And for me it was clear that I was being called home to the legal system. Not in a full-time capacity. But in the slow work of advocating for one kid, one case at a time. That is the work of a CASA. I’m not quitting my day job. I’m just grateful to be stepping back into the work I’m passionate about alongside people I so admire as a volunteer. 

There goes God again. Never dropping a single plot point in our lives. You guys. It was a MOMENT ♥️

Whatever’s going on outside the frame. God is with you—it’s literally what Christ’s name means. 

The word “Emmanuel” comes from the Greek rendering of two Hebrew words, `immanu, “with us,” and ‘el, “God” (thus in English it is found as either “Emmanuel” or “Immanuel”).

Matthew 1:23 “Behold, the virgin shall conceive and bear a son, and they shall call his name Immanuel’ (which means, God with us).”

With you. Wherever you are right now. Whatever’s going on. In all of it.

Couldn’t go to sleep without reminding you about that tonight.

Can’t stop thinking about close friends and so many others out there who are all keeping watch by the weird dichotomy of twinkle lights and ICU monitors this Christmas season. It’s a real mind bender. And a faith bender. Here’s some of what I was texting a most deeply precious old friend whose headed into their third week with their daughter in the ICU. Maybe it’s for you too? 

Jesus of the dirt and the donkeys, 
the blood, and a mother’s cries
God of the ICU 
Lord of the IV and the night shift
Brother of the port, the catheter, the bedside, 
the waiting room, the OR
Breathe over us 
Be as close as DNA
And doubt
And angel choirs 
And sheep dung. 
God over glucose and dialysis and doctors 
Lean over parents who wail in lonely cars in 
hospital parking lots
Exhale faith back into our lungs.
Lord we remember your name in the night
Put your promise back in our mouths.
Mary’s son, “man of suffering, and familiar with pain”
Have mercy on our bodies, broken with you.

Christmas as a ransom story has always made more sense to me than as a lullaby. In the words of @philipyanceyofficial —“On earth a baby was born, a king got wind of it, a chase ensued. In heaven the Great Invasion had begun, a daring raid by the ruler of the forces of good into the universe’s seat of evil.”

It’s a love story. A rescue story. A plot where the hero gave up EVERYTHING for you, before you even knew his name. So he’s not looking for you pretty, your presents, your clean kitchen, year end goals met or sparkly life. 

He came for you. Failing, fearful, worried, quirky, funny, delightful, “am I living up to my potential”, self-harming, self-hating, brilliant, fired, cheating, angry, angsty, all the versions of you, YOU. 

A man once infamous for hating everything about Jesus put it this way—

“And in love he chose us before he laid the foundation of the universe! Because of his great love, he ordained us, so that we would be seen as holy in his eyes with an unstained innocence.” Ephesians 1:4 TPT

NYE resolutions make me tired. Here’s to those of us who enter the new year without much hype. 
Who aren’t inspired by big goals. 
Who don’t buy into new year, new you. 
We know there will be monsters and heroes ahead. 
No matter what the plan is. 
But there will also be hope. 
Thanks to the God who is still in the slow business of making all broken stories and humans new.

Been texting with one of my oldest friends from back home in South Africa. We became moms the same year, 18 years ago. At the time we didn’t know each other well. Let’s be real, we barely knew ourselves. Church was a complicated story then. And I was stranded between a homecoming to my home country that didn’t last and a return to America that I didn’t want. We were both low on sleep and faith.. I left. She stayed. We both had two more kids. 

In the nearly 2 decades since then our paths continue to cross whenever I am back home, and we catch up with brutal honesty. Much of the fluff of our faith has fallen away since we were baby parents. What remains is the core. The stuff that can take hit after hit of loss or shock or sorrow or suffering. Because it’s the ground Jesus stands on. Rock bottom is Jesus’ territory. 

There has been beauty too. Joy. Our children growing muscles and wings. And from my living room in Maryland by the light of the Christmas tree at night I text with her in the three weeks she spends in an ICU room with her daughter. I don’t dare text her fluff or Christianese or happily ever after. We’ve outgrown that. We know how it feels to cry in empty cars in hospital parking lots. And we know Jesus. And still He holds. 

As the page turns on the story and into another new year I hope you know that whatever room you find yourself in on December 31st— your living room, a hospital room, a church, a ballroom, a kitchen, or a parked car—Jesus is the God who came in person, in DNA, in dirty feet and sweaty ordinary armpits to be with you. in all your stories this year. 

I have no other way to explain it other than we believe in Jesus — the Son of suffering. And his intimacy defies the lie that prosperity or health = blessing. 

And instead the terrible tender truth is that, “𝗕𝗹𝗲𝘀𝘀𝗲𝗱 are those who 𝙢𝙤𝙪𝙧𝙣 for 𝙩𝙝𝙚𝙮 shall be comforted.” Matthew 5:4 

May the turning of the page be gentle on you, dear heart. You are so beloved.

Your life is full of edits, not mistakes. Take it from this acquisitions editor, friends, the best stories come from those who aren’t afraid of the rewrites. 

May your year be full of courageous rewrites. We aren’t doomed to relive old stories, patterns, choices, behaviors. Jesus is my favorite storyteller and editor and I believe you can trust him with your plot twists. And all your rewrites this year. He’s never met a loose thread He isn’t willing to go back and rewrite into a better story. Trust me on this.

My dad would come home from delivering babies or stitching up fingers or simply listening to the aches of his patients, and go straight into the garden. In his patent leather shoes. With a peach in his hand, a huge hunk bitten off and chewing in his cheek. 

He’d wade into the weeds, pulling as he went, flicking that peach pit high and far, like the arc of one winking eye in the sky. He’d crouch down next to the Koi Pond and scoop algae, sprinkle fish food, mutter at the dogs following him too closely. 

He’d kneel and his dress pants would get damp and creased and still he’d lean too far over the water, watching for the flash of his fish. Then he’d climb the stone steps up to the trees he was trying to train to go straight again, their stems slow to obey.

I never paid much attention. He’d call to me, as I lay in front of the TV, to come and see some tree or fish or worse yet sit next to him at dusk on a bench he’d built into the side of the hill. It irritated me something wild to be interrupted like that. 

I was 20. And still lived in South Africa. Now there’s an ocean and three decades between us and I can still remember those nights. 

I guess all I’m saying now in my wordy way is — don’t be afraid to interrupt your kids and drag them into random moments with you. They’re only annoyed on the surface. Underneath they are being imprinted with you. And you teens and twenty something’s — say yes more often. 

Decades later you’ll wish you did.

I couldn’t speak to the first boy I ever loved. I was 18 and I’d drive my dad’s old green VW station wagon with the windows down listening to Bon Jovi. I had a tape deck and a mouth full of all the words I didn’t know how to say out loud. 

You can be nearly 50 and still remember your first love story. When you’re driving home with the car full of your teenagers and their music thrumming through the seat. You’ll never forget how he sat at your desk and sipped hot chocolate and how his eyes missed nothing about you. How grateful you’ll always be for that first whisper of love that echoed through an 18 year old’s worst year. But you will grow up and grow away from that boy and come home to yourself and a man who made you his home. 

And then one Sunday as you drive back from church with the three who call you home now you’ll remember that long ago boy and his blonde bangs and his music as your car hums with teenagers and their favorite songs. And you’ll smile as the sun warms your hands on the wheel and the voices and feet tapping from the back seat warm your insides. 

At 18 you can’t imagine a love story where you’re not the main character. At nearly 50 you sit in the front row as your children take center stage and it is fascinating to watch these bits and pieces of your own story find their voices. They don’t know that you hear yourself echoing in their questions and love and fashion choices.

You watch them becoming all the ages you once were and there is no stopping it. The car thrums with their confidence and lyrics and you smile as you listen to them and all that they don’t know is still coming. 

All the 2am conversations and late night burger runs and first kisses and bank accounts and broken hearts and misunderstandings and making up and trying again and moving cross country and first keys and last classes and new books and old friends and it’s coming for them. Like it did for you. 

You can’t protect them from it. You can barely prepare them for it. So you turn up the volume. You remember this moment. This car. These lyrics, this love story we’re all in the middle of.
